708854f-a.text:
Fifth Avenue, east side, north from East 45th Street (right, not included). At the right is the Church of the Heavenly Rest (No. 551) that was built through the efforts of Dr. Robt. S. Howland then the Rector of the Church of the Holy Apostles. The parish originated in services held in the Hall of Rutgers Female College (q.v.) in 1865. Cast across the front, is the shadow of the Church of the Divine Paternity (Universalist) that stood at the S.W. corner of 45th Street. In the center is Windsor Hotel, prior to its destructive fire in 1899. The construction shown beyond is for the new St. Patricks Cathedral that was protected by Archbishop Hughs in 1850 from plans by James Renwick. The cornerstone was laid in 1858 and opened in 1879. 1892 saw it nearly completed with the exclusion of the Lady Chapel. The steeples were added in 1888.

Possibly 1888
Collection of George T. Bagoe
86 Madison Ave., N.Y.C.

708848f-a.text:
North on Fifth Avenue from 45th Street.

Of all the five churches shown in this picture, the Protestant-Episcopal Church of the Heavenly Rest (at right) has been demolished, while St. Thomas's Protestant-Episcopal Church (second spire on left side of street) has burned and been rebuilt.

The other three still stand.
1893.

Photograph by Brown Brothers.

708841f-a.text:
Fifth Avenue, North on East Side from 45th Street, showing the Protestant Episcopal Church of the Heavenly Rest. This Church and the corner buildings were demolished in 1928 to make way for building now located on the same site, erected by Fred F. French.

1907.
Photographs by Brown Brothers.

708849f-b.text:
Fifth Avenue, west side, north from 45th Street, a night view.
Among the shops and office buildings the spire of the Collegiate
Church, on the N.W. corner of 46th Street, stands out like
a dark shadow.  The slowness of the lens makes this photo-
graph an interesting study of automobile traffic in motion.
April 22, 1931

New York Edison Company Collection
NO REPRODUCTIONS.
